The Carolina Wren data used by Royle et al. (2012)

These data come from the North American Breeding Bird Survey.

Royle, J.A., R.B. Chandler, C. Yackulic and J. D. Nichols. 2012. Likelihood analysis of species occurrence probability from presence-only data for modelling species distributions. Methods in Ecology and Evolution. doi: 10.1111/j.2041-210X.2011.00182.x

Fake data for the Maunga Whau volcano

Based upon volcano in the datasets package with no coordinate system attributes

Model occurrence probability using presence-only data

This function estimates the probability of occurrence using presence-only data and spatially-referenced covariates. Species distribution maps can be created by plotting the expected values of occurrence probability. The model is described by Royle et al. (2012).

Warning: Maximizing the log-likelihood function is achieved using the optim function, which can fail to nd the global optima if sensible starting values are not supplied. The default starting values are rep(0, npars), which will often be adequate if the covariates have been standardized. Standardizing covariates is thus recommended. Even when covariates are standardized, it is always a good idea to try various starting values to see if the log-likelihood can be increased. When tting models with many parameters, good starting values can be found by tting simpler models rst.

Note: 1.)Points and rasters should the same coordinate system. The program does not check this so it is up to the user.2.)The MAXENT software assumes that species prevalence is known a priori. If the user does not specify a value for prevalence, prevalence is set to 0.5. MAXENT predictions of occurrence probability are highly sensitive to this setting. In contrast, maxlike directly estimates prevalence.
